<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Redman Presents U.S. Initiatives to Granic </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602194394 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1602194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Mate Granic, Croatian deputy prime minister and 
foreign minister, has received the U.S. President's special 
envoy Charles Redman. Mr. Redman informed Granic about U.S. 
views on the possibilities for resolving the crisis in this part 
of Europe, especially in Bosnia-Herzegovina, in the light of the 
latest NATO decisions. 
  Ambassador Redman presented several U.S. initiatives -- also 
supported by the leading countries of the European Union -- for 
setting up Croat-Muslim relations on a lasting basis and for 
ending the war in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  Minister Granic voiced Croatia's support for NATO's resolve 
to end the conflict in Bosnia-Herzegovina as soon as possible. 
Hope was expressed that all parties to the conflict -- 
especially the Serb side -- would take the world community's 
warnings seriously. 
  Both sides attached particular importance to the setting up 
of Croat-Muslim relations and cooperation between the two 
peoples in the final resolution of the crisis. Ambassador 
Redman laid special emphasis on the importance the United States 
was attaching to Croatia's role in resolving the crisis in these 
parts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

