<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK President Protests to Mitterrand </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602150794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1356 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602150794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 16 (TANJUG) -- President of the 
Republic of Serb Krajina (RSK) Milan Martic, in his letter of 
protest to French President Francois Mitterrand, warns him that 
his government is to be blamed for the possible fresh genocide 
of Serbs because of a partial policy of Paris towards the 
Serbian people and their states which emerged from the collapse 
of ex-Yugoslavia. 
  France has waged a strong campaign for the NATO forces to 
air 
raid positions of the Serbs in the ex-Yugoslav republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  On February 9, NATO 'succumbed' to France's pressure but, to 
the disappointment of Paris, it threatened with air strikes 
equally against the Bosnian Muslims as well as the Bosnian Serbs 
unless they withdraw by February 20 their heavy weapons in and 
around Sarajevo, or regroup them and place them under UNPROFOR 
(U.N. Protection Force) control. 
  In his letter to Mitterrand, monitored by the RSK news 
agency 
ISKRA, Martic is confident that the current French policy will 
lose the battle because it contradicts the spirit of France's 
freedom, not because it is unjust towards the Serbs. 
  Martic said that back in 1876 the celebrated French poet 
Victor Hugo accused Europe of helping to annihilate Serbs in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and that he sought protection for Serbs while 
European civilization would save its face. 
  Martic also recalled the notable French politicians and 
generals in the past who were enthusiastic about the way the 
Serbs were fighting on their side in World War One. 
  "May I remind you that the Serbian people have built a 
monument to the French state, perhaps the only such monument in 
the world. It represents France as the state of victory and 
democracy, with which the Serbian people were allied in the two 
world wars," Martic writes. 
  Last January, Martic was elected president of the RSK, the 
state proclaimed in predominantly Serb-populated parts of the 
former Croatia in response to its violent secession and its 
attempt to reduce their civil and national rights. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

