<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Serbia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Sees `Much Better' Sarajevo Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602195494 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1800 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1602195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [News conference by Vitaliy Churkin, Russian deputy foreign </F>
minister, after his talks with Serbian President Slobodan 
Milosevic in Belgrade on 16 February; all questions and answers 
are in English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian translation -- 
recorded] 
  [Text] [Churkin] President Milosevic and I spoke mostly 
about Sarajevo and other issues concerning a political solution 
for Bosnia-Herzegovina. I expect to see him again later today 
or tomorrow. 
  [Unidentified reporter] Are you being successful in your 
diplomacy? 
  [Churkin] I think that I am, but, to be more serious, it is 
too early to speak about success. We are looking at all the 
aspects of the situation around Sarajevo. 
  Having been to Sarajevo yesterday, yes, I am satisfied. The 
situation on the ground is much better. There is peace in the 
city. It is fragile but is nevertheless peace. We are doing 
everything that we can to make it a firmer and more lasting 
peace, not only in Sarajevo, but throughout Bosnia. 

</TEXT>

