<F P=100> MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crvenkovski Applies to Join `Partnership' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602200994 Paris AFP in English 1955 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602200994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, Feb 16 (AFP) -- The Macedonian Government 
has asked to join NATO's Partnership for Peace, an official said 
Wednesday [16 February], as NATO member Greece clamped a partial 
economic embargo on the former Yugoslav republic. 
  The official said Macedonian Foreign Minister Stevo 
Crvenkovski had informed North Atlantic Treaty Organisation 
secretary-general Manfred Woerner by letter of Skopje's 
intention to join the partnership and participate in it actively. 
  The partnership, announced by NATO last month, provides for 
military cooperation and aid especially for former communist 
countries in eastern Europe, with the possibility of full 
membership later. 
  Observers here said the partnership could lead to Macedonia 
providing U.S. and NATO bases on its soil. 

</TEXT>

