<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olechowski Addresses Senate on East Europe Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702103094 Warsaw PAP in Polish 0926 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1702103094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, 17 Feb--Addressing a meeting of the Senate 
Foreign Affairs Commission today, Andrzej Olechowski, minister 
of foreign affairs, presented the main assumptions of Poland's 
eastern policy. 
  Olechowski said that the policy toward East Europe should 
focus on developing good relations with countries important from 
the point of view of Polish political and economic interests and 
the country's security. 
  "Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, the Baltic states, Moldova, and 
Kazakhstan form the group of states that are of particular 
interest to us," Olechowski said. 
  According to the minister, support for political and 
military 
stability in the region and the creation of new possibilities 
for beneficial economic cooperation are among the important 
goals of Poland's eastern policy. 

</TEXT>

