<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Solidarity Says Union Can `Strike Until Victory' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS1602150994 Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA in Polish 16 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> WS1602150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw RZECZPOSPOLITA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by B.I.W.: "Ready For a `Strike Until Victory'"] </F>
  [Text] The Presidium of the National Committee [KK] of 
"Solidarity" ["S"] stated that "the success of the 9 February 
demonstration, the social support that was achieved, must not be 
wasted." Today the KK will make a decision concerning further 
action of the trade union. "Marian Krzaklewski stated that a 
strategic strike would be possible; such a strike would force 
the authorities to make decisions favorable to employees. 
Nothing seems to show that this demonstration has made any 
impression on the government, which we expected: There are no 
preparations for talks or any serious corrections of the 
budget," we learned from KK Press Spokesman Piotr Zak after the 
Tuesday [15 February] session of the Presidium. 
  On Tuesday, Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak replied to 
Krzaklewski (who proposed negotiations in order to "avoid the 
escalation of social tension") that "a bad tradition, inherited 
from the former years, is the transferring of each conflict to 
the central level." This is why their meeting "should be 
preceded by a debate on the scope of the problems that may be 
discussed in a different mode and that call for an official 
meeting." He added that difficult problems should be resolved 
"in a working mode" and that such talks are already being held 
by the Labor Ministry. 
  For "S," Pawlak's letter is no answer, as it were. He 
already proposed that they resume negotiations on social 
guarantees, but, in this matter, "they presented their opinion 
and submitted conditions that have so far been impossible to 
implement." 
  What can a "strategic strike" be like? "We realize that it 
is no longer the time or not yet the time for us to be able to 
"galvanize to action" the entire country. However, we are a 
well-organized and strong union and we are able to continue a 
strike until we win. One can imagine, for example, the strike 
of several branches or several regions of great importance to 
the country, or a progressive strike in all the regions of "S." 
Or merging all these three strike forms and demonstrations," 
says Zak. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

