<F P=100> POLAND </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mutual Employment Agreement Signed With Ukraine </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602162894 Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network in Polish 1105 
GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1602162894 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw Radio Warszawa Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Polish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Presenter] Leszek Miller and Mykhaylo Kaskevych, 
ministers of labor of Poland and Ukraine, have signed an 
agreement on mutual employment. 
  [Correspondent Magdalena Winiarczyk] The agreement, which 
has 
been signed for a three-year period, sets the conditions for 
legal employment. Any form of employment that does not comply 
with the principles of the agreement is illegal. The period of 
individual employment may not be longer than 12 months and, in 
exceptional circumstances, can be extended to 18 months. The 
pay and working conditions for foreign employees may not be 
worse than the conditions enjoyed by the citizens of each 
country. This is to prevent dumping practices. Social 
security, health care and legal protection are to be guaranteed 
by the employing country and are to be included in consular 
conventions. 
  Work permits are to be issued by employment offices for 
specific employers and specific jobs. This principle also 
concerns applications for long-stay visas, which include work 
permits as well. 
  Ministers Leszek Miller and Mykhaylo Kaskevych have also 
signed an agreement on cooperation in the area of labor and 
social policy between the two countries. 
  [Announcer] Magdalena Winiarczyk was speaking from the 
Ministry of Labor for the Midday Magazine. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

