<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister To Act Against Embargo Violations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602094094 Sofia BTA in English 2234 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602094094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 15 (BTA) -- The Ministry of 
Transport is going to adopt stern measures against embargo 
busting, Transport Minister Kiril Ermenkov told a news 
conference today. There have been embargo busting attempts 
involving railway employees and border guard members, Minister 
Ermenkov said, adding that the cases were reported by anonymous 
informers. "It is our ambition to guarantee the prevention of 
any attempts to violate the embargo," the minister said. 
  The measures which the Transport Ministry is planning to 
implement are specified in a special report which will be 
presented to the Sanctions Committee. 
  An organization is set up by special order to exercise 
control at the border checkpoints, it comprises representatives 
of the Ministry of Transport, the Ministry of Finance and the 
Ministry of the Interior. Besides, it is planned to handle 
cargoes only in daytime, the cargo handling will be monitored by 
operative groups. 
  Bulgaria is ready for transit shipments across the territory 
of ex-Yugoslavia, Minister Ermenkov said. However, having in 
mind the complicated situation in Bosnia, such shipments will be 
effected in the last resort. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

