<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zieleniec Supports NATO Ultimatum on B-H </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602142194 Prague CTK in English 2323 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 15 (CTK) -- Czech Foreign Minister 
Josef Zieleniec said today he believed that in view of the NATO 
Council's decision about possible air strikes in Bosnia the 
Czech Republic should at least symbolically stand by its allies. 
  It is impossible to speak about NATO countries as of 
potential partners and allies and in a situation when they have 
to take a complicated decision to distance itself from them, 
Zieleniec told the Czech Television station NOVA. 
  He said not only air strikes were concerned but an ultimatum 
that should lead to separation of the warring sides. "Sarajevo 
is a town experiencing awful sufferings, the town which is being 
strangled. I believe this action could lead to Sarajevo being 
relieved and that is why I support it," Zieleniec said. 
  On February 10, the NATO Council approved a communique 
giving 
a ten-day ultimatum to Bosnian Serbs and Muslims to withdraw 
their heavy weapons and put them under UNPROFOR [United Nations 
Protection Force] control, otherwise they would be subject to 
air strikes. 

</TEXT>

