<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Slovak Measure Jeopardizes Customs Union </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602074994 Prague CTK in English 2116 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602074994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 15 (CTK) -- The Czech Parliamentary 
Agricultural Committee sent a letter to its Slovak counterpart 
body today requesting that it push for the cancellation of the 
requirement that food products imported into Slovakia carry a 
Slovak quality certificate. 
  Slovakia introduced the requirement unilaterally and with 
only one day's notice on February 11. 
  In the letter chairman of the Czech Parliamentary 
Agricultural Committee Jan Cerny told Pavel Koncos that the new 
measure "quite clearly discriminates against Czech exporters of 
food products." 
  The move also seriously interfered with the functioning of 
the customs union between the Czech Republic and Slovakia, he 
said, because the quality norms of both countries were the same 
and because the basis of any customs union was mutual 
recognition of the other state's laboratory analysis and 
certification. 
  Cerny stated that he hoped the Slovak Parliamentary 
Agricultural Committee would contribute to the requirement being 
revoked or to the drawing up of an agreement in the interests of 
preserving the customs union. 

</TEXT>

