<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ducky: Slovaks To Drop Requirement </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702064694 Prague CTK in English 1617 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702064694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 16 (CTK) -- Slovak Finance Minister 
Julius Toth will make a statement in the near future confirming 
that the Slovak customs authorities recognize quality 
certificates issued in the Czech Republic as they did before 
February 11, when the Slovak measure under which all food 
exporters, including Czechs, were required to produce a quality 
certificate at the Slovak border, came into effect. 
  This was announced at a news conference of Slovak Economics 
Minister Jan Ducky and chairman of the Council of the 
Czech-Slovak Customs Union following its extraordinary session 
today. The conference was attended by six Czech and Slovak 
ministers. 
  Both sides will meet before March 31 to iron out an 
agreement 
of the individual criteria which Slovak quality certificates 
must meet in the Czech Republic, and vice versa. 
  The ministers said only one percent of their countries' 
mutual trade still needed to be coordinated at the future 
meeting, because for the other 99 percent of goods the 
certificate question had already been resolved. 
  The Czech representatives at the meeting had requested the 
Slovak Customs Administration reconsider its decision to require 
the certification of all imported goods by domestic inspectors. 
Czech Agriculture Minister Josef Lux informed reporters of the 
Czech contingents' intentions before the meeting. 

</TEXT>

