<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Approves Nuclear Agreements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502211194 Prague CTK in English 1846 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502211194 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, February 15 (CTK) -- The Czech Parliament 
today approved a government bill whereby the Czech Republic 
accedes to the Vienna Agreement of 1963 on civic and legal 
responsibility for nuclear damage, and to the joint protocol on 
the validity of the Vienna and Paris Agreements. 
  The agreements contain the legal regulation of 
responsibility 
for nuclear damage in countries which already have the relevant 
legislation. Their aim is the creation of an international 
system of responsibility and harmonization of nuclear 
legislation, and a system offering the public protection and 
ensuring fast and effective compensation to those damaged. 
  Industry and Trade Minister Vladimir Dlouhy (ODA) said that 
acceding to the agreement would, among other things, eliminate 
the possibility of international conflicts. 
  The Vienna Agreement, concluded on May 21, 1963 is open to 
all UN states, and has 19 members. The Paris Agreement, valid 
as of April 1, 1968, associates 16 states. The two agreements 
have fundamentally the same principles, but differ in their 
wording in some places. They also differ as to the amount 
payable for damages. 

</TEXT>

