<H3> <TI>   Poll Reflects Coalition Election Victory </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502182294 Prague CTK in English 1304 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 15 (CTK) -- The government coalition 
parties would obtain a total of 52.5 percent of the votes, a 
poll conducted by the Center of Empirical Research (STEM) in 
early February revealed. The turn-out would be 75 percent, the 
poll showed. 
  The Civic Democratic Party (ODS, Premier Vaclav Klaus) would 
get 31.3 percent of the votes, the Civic Democratic Alliance 
(ODA) 14.3 percent, the Christian Democratic Union-Czechoslovak 
People's Party (KDU-CSL) 5.4 percent, and the Christian 
Democratic Party (KDS) 1.5 percent. 
  The opposition would fare as follows: The Czech Social 
Democratic Party (CSSD) 13.9 percent, the Left Bloc (primarily 
Communists) 10.9, the Assembly for the Republic-Czechoslovak 
Republican Party (SPR-RSC, leader Miroslav Sladek) 3.7 percent. 

</TEXT>

