<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak Comments on Personnel, Budget Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602203494 Warsaw PAP in English 1905 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602203494 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 16 -- Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
denied during a press conference on Wednesday that he was was 
planning to appoint a government press spokesman in the near 
future. Pawlak said the appointment of a finance minister would 
be discussed by the coalition of the Democratic Left Alliance 
(SLD) and the Polish Peasant Party (PSL). 
  The prime minister said he was not planning to make any 
personnel changes in the Ministry of Privatization as recently 
"it considerably changed its style of work" and "the changes in 
its leadership were very profound." 
  Asked about appointments of coalition deputy ministers in 
the 
so-called presidential ministries, Pawlak said: "We are not 
priding ourselves on certain matters but there are some 
achievements." He also suggested that newsmen should 
concentrate on the functioning of these institutions and not on 
symbols. 
  Pawlak said that in case of possible amendments to the 
budget 
law in mid-1994, if incomes were bigger than planned, he would 
spend the money to animate the economy and on significant social 
goals, namely, social assistance and combatting unemployment. 
  When told that the decisions of the Sejm Budget Committee 
adopted on Wednesday were contradictory to his announcements of 
the "pro-social budget," Pawlak stressed that press reports on 
the cabinet amendments were incomplete. He also recalled that 
education, science and culture were planned to receive the 
biggest possible means. The prime minister also added that if 
it were not for the internal indebtedness, the state budget 
would be balanced. 
  While speaking about a Polish visit by the mission of the 
International Monetary Fund (IMF), Pawlak stressed that Poland 
fulfilled the conditions included in the agreement. He also 
added that the success did not depend on such agreements but "on 
the way we control social and economic processes in Poland." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31398 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu033__a94024" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EEU-94-033-A </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 February 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Friendship Treaty Initialed With Moldova </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1502191194 Warsaw PAP in English 1554 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1502191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 15 -- Polish Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski and his Moldovan counterpart Ion Botnaru, now on an 
official visit to this country, initialled on Tuesday a treaty 
on friendship and cooperation between Poland and Moldova. The 
two ministers also signed a protocol on mutual consultations 
between their ministries. Olechowski said that the treaty would 
be signed in the first half of this year during a Polish visit 
by Moldovan President Mircea Snegur. 
  The Polish foreign minister stressed that relations with 
Moldova -- like the ones with the neighbouring countries and 
kazakhstan -- were considered by Poland as top priority of the 
Polish foreign policy towards the states established after the 
break-up of the Soviet Union. 
  Olechowski added Poland wanted to help Moldova consolidate 
its presence on the international arena as it was security of 
"such states as Moldova" in which Poland saw a significant 
condition of its own security and favourable development of 
European relations. 
  The Polish foreign minister said Poland would open its 
embassy in Chisinau still this year. 
  Next, Olechowski said that during the Polish-Moldovan talks 
the two sides discussed the necessity to improve living 
conditions of the Polish minority in Moldova, to provide 
possibilities of learning the Polish language and to ensure 
Poles access to national culture. 
  The two sides also spoke about prospects of economic 
cooperation, especially between small and medium-sized 
enterprises. Botnaru said he hoped Moldova could make use of 
the Polish experience in introducing market reforms. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

