<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pawlak, Olechowski on Foreign Policy Priorities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602131194 Warsaw PAP in English 1251 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 16--Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak and 
Foreign Minister Andrzej Olechowski discussed the current 
priorities of the Polish foreign policy and the present 
situation in Poland during a meeting held Wednesday with 
ambassadors to the countries of NATO, the European Union and the 
European Free Trade Association (EFTA). 
  Pawlak stressed the need for Poland's increased effort to 
join western structures, and above all for intensified strivings 
for NATO and the EU membership. He also discussed the question 
of Poland's participation in the "Partnership for Peace" 
programme. 
  The prime minister confirmed in the presence of the 
ambassadors the Polish Government's guarantees for western 
investors and assured that the government would respect any 
agreements that were or will be concluded with them. 
  Foreign Minister Olechowski told newsmen that the two-day 
session of Polish diplomats will centre on the question of 
Poland's security and her closer contacts with the European 
Union which are crucial elements of the Polish foreign policy 
which the ambassadors attending the meeting will frequently have 
to deal with. 
  According to Olechowski, the meeting should help the 
ambassadors learn about the approach of the "state's top 
figures" to the problems of foreign policy. The foreign 
minister also said he expected information from the ambassadors 
on the existing possibilities in Poland's contacts with western 
countries. 

</TEXT>

