<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik: `Mere Technical Problem' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602173894 Prague CTK in English 1558 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602173894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 16 (CTK) -- "I consider my 
withdrawal from the government and the Movement for a Democratic 
Slovakia (HZDS) to be a mere technical problem," Slovak Foreign 
Minister Jozef Moravcik told journalists today. 
  He said he did not intend to leave the political life since 
he felt he shared responsibility for the appearance of the 
independent Slovakia. "I wanted Slovakia to become independent 
and contributed to this goal. I therefore cannot leave the 
political scene until a political structure capable of 
guaranteeing stability and prosperity for Slovakia is created," 
Moravcik said. 
  He said he expected new groupings to appear on the Slovak 
political scene in the near future and mainly a strong bloc of 
center-oriented parties. Moravcik said the HZDS had deflected 
from the central line and has been lately oriented towards 
radicalism. He said he was for central policy but declined to 
say which political party he would prefer. 
  Slovak Premier Vladimir Meciar did not specify at any of 
government meetings his allegations that "the opposition is 
connected with financial circles," which were raised by him in 
the media, Moravcik said. On the contrary, a quick decision by 
the government on Tuesday [15 February] to put fifteen 
state-owned enterprises to direct sale testifies to Meciar's 
"genuine intention" to proceed with privatization in a honest 
way, Moravcik added ironically. 
  Commenting on his "voluntary walk-out" from a government 
session on Tuesday, Moravcik said that he and Deputy Premier 
Roman Kovac were called upon by Meciar to leave the second part 
of the meeting, "if they are honest people," since it was 
dedicated to internal political situation. 

</TEXT>

