<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Election Proposals Contrasted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602174294 Prague CTK in English 1657 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 16 (CTK) -- The basic difference 
between the government and deputies' bills on early elections 
lies in the date of the elections. While the government 
proposes to hold early elections in June, the deputies' bill 
envisages them on November 11-12. Both proposals will be 
discussed today. 
  The government bill proposes that parliament electoral term 
and the mandates of deputies elected to the now-defunct 
Czechoslovak Federal Parliament two years ago terminate by June 
30. It justifies shortening the electoral term and calling 
early elections by the fact that the current distribution of 
forces in parliament does not allow laws to be passed, as both 
the government coalition and the opposition have about 75 
mandates in the 150-member parliament. 
  According to the bill, early elections would cost about 150 
million crowns ($5 million). If parliamentary elections are 
held simultaneously with local elections the total expenditure 
would amount to 180 million crowns (some $6 million). About 100 
million crowns would be saved if parliamentary and local 
elections were prepared together, according to the government 
bill. 
  If the two strongest parliamentary parties -- the governing 
Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) and Democratic Left 
Party (SDL) -- failed to agree on the date for early elections 
and if the deputies' proposal was supported by the opposition 
and the government bill by representatives of the coalition 
(HZDS and part of the Slovak National Party, SNS) then nine 
votes of the "fresh dissidents" from the ranks of the HZDS could 
prove decisive. 
  Speculation has also appeared that deputies from the 
Hungarian minority parties -- the Hungarian Christian Democratic 
Movement (MKDH) and the Egyutteles (Coexistence) movement -- 
could support the government proposal since they are sure of 
support from their voters irrespective of the current political 
situation in the country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

