<H3> <TI>   Government Cancels Travel Agreement With FRY </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502213994 Prague CTK in English 1821 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502213994 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 15 (CTK) -- The Slovak Government has 
recently annulled the agreement on non-visa contact signed by 
Czechoslovakia and the former Yugoslavia, CTK learnt today from 
a diplomatic source in Belgrade who did not wish to be named. 
  The source was not able to say whether the agreement, signed 
by two now defunct states, had been rescinded in order to make 
way for a replacement document or whether the move represented 
the introduction of visa requirement for certain republics of 
ex-Yugoslavia, as the Czech Republic has already done. The 
usually well-informed source believes the latter possibility 
more likely. 
  It is not clear which republics are concerned or when the 
new 
visa requirements will come into effect. 
  The Czech Republic introduced visa requirement for citizens 
of the new Yugoslav Republic (Serbia and Montenegro), and 
Bosnia-Herzegovina on June 23 last year. 

</TEXT>

