<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Impact of Import Restrictions on Trade Balance </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1502203094 Prague CTK in English 1639 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1502203094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 15 (CTK) -- The requirement that 
food products imported into Slovakia have a quality certificate, 
introduced unilaterally last week, has been interpreted wrongly, 
director of the Customs Union Council (RCU) Secretariat Rudolf 
Besik told CTK today. 
  The measure is nothing new and not in conflict with 
legislation, Besik said. The problems that have resulted are 
due only to insufficient preparation. He said the measure could 
not influence Slovakia's trade balance. 
  Food products make up only 8 or 9 percent of total 
Slovak-Czech trade. The share food products have in the Czech 
Republic's trade surplus in the mutual balance of payments only 
amounts to 2.5 billion Slovak crowns, Besik reported. 
  An exceptional RCU meeting could, he said, decide on the 
recognition of the quality certificate which the Czech 
Agricultural and Food Inspectorate (CZPI) has been issuing. 
This could mean that Slovakia would drop its certificate 
requirement with regard to the Czech Republic, he said. 
  Besik said he did not know the location or date of the RCU 
extraordinary meeting, when asked to confirm Government 
Spokesman Ondrej Hanka's statement that the economics minister 
had been requested to convene the meeting for February 16. 
  Quality certification for the import of food products into 
Slovakia came into effect on February 11. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

