<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karadzic: War `Is Finally Over' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702191494 Belgrade RTB Television Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1830 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1702191494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade RTB Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statements by Vitaliy Churkin, deputy foreign minister of </F>
Russia, and Radovan Karadzic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs, at a 
news conference in Pale on 17 February; both statements are in 
English with superimposed Serbo-Croatian translation -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Churkin] I have today brought to Belgrade and Pale 
a letter from President Yeltsin. This letter is addressed to 
President Milosevic, Dr. Karadzic, and other Serb leaders, as 
well as the Serbian people. It contains Russia's request that, 
in the interest of halting the bloodshed, the Serbian side 
withdraw its heavy weapons from Sarajevo. 
  In that context, the Russian Federation would be prepared to 
send its troops to the Sarajevo area to participate in the UN 
peace operation. I am glad to state that this Russian 
initiative, which we believe is in the interests of both the 
Muslims and the Serbs and all the people of Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
has been accepted by the Serbian side. We hope that the 
acceptance of the Russian initiative will put an end to the 
crisis around Sarajevo and we know that this will be a major 
step toward the overall settlement of the war in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  [Karadzic] I would like to say that we are very grateful to 
Russia for its involvement in the crisis. We have accepted the 
proposal put forward by Russia regarding the withdrawal of the 
heavy weapons. We also think that further Russian participation 
in the conference and the peace process will be welcomed and 
fruitful. 
  We are going to do what we will do on the basis of, first of 
all, the Russian demands, which for us mean certain guarantees, 
and then on the basis of our agreement with Mr. Akashi of 7 
February and the Serbian-Muslim agreement of 9 February. We 
think that the war in Sarajevo is finally over. 

</TEXT>

