<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ganic Says Russians `Not Welcome' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702214294 Paris AFP in English 2125 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702214294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, Feb 17 (AFP) -- Russian troops are not 
neutral and are "not welcome" on the Bosnian Serb frontlines in 
Sarajevo, Bosnian Vice President Ejup Ganic said Thursday [17 
February]. 
  Ganic was asked for his reaction to Thursday's agreement for 
the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw heavy weaponry from Sarajevo, 
following Russian mediation. In return, the Russians are to 
send peacekeeping troops to Bosnia. 
  Ganic said: "The Russians are not neutral and have never 
agreed with NATO on the demilitarisation process of Sarajevo. 
Therefore, they are not welcome." 
  Ganic said that if the Russian troops were deployed in the 
Sarajevo region, he would prefer "to see them guarding Bosnian 
heavy weapons placed under UN control rather than Serb weapons." 
  The North Atlantic Treaty Organisation has threatened to 
bomb 
the Serb artillery from 2400 GMT Sunday if it were not withdrawn 
from around Sarajevo or put under control of the UN Protection 
Force (UNPROFOR). 
  The Bosnian army is mainly Moslem. The Russian government 
has come under domestic pressure to support the Serbs who are 
fellow Slavs and orthodox Christians. 
  Ganic added that the Russian initiative was "clumsy from a 
diplomatic point of view because it shows a lack of trust in the 
UNPROFOR", the UN Protection Force in former Yugoslavia. 
  Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, speaking in Athens 
on Thursday, said the Moslem side should now make concessions. 
  "The time has come for the West to prove that it knows how 
to 
do something better than an ultimatum, by encouraging the other 
side to undertake what we have obtained from the Serbs," he told 
journalists before holding talks with his German counterpart 
Klaus Kinkel. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

