<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Details Control Measures for Heavy Weapons </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702184094 Paris AFP in English 1817 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702184094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] United Nations, Feb 17 (AFP) -- UN Protection Forces 
(UNPROFOR) will rely on armed ground forces established at 
several sites to ensure control of Bosnian Serb weapons around 
Sarajevo, a UN spokesman said Thursday [17 February]. 
  UN control "will be achieved through permanent, on the 
ground 
UNPROFOR armed presence on five or six established sites on each 
side where heavy weapons are regrouped," UN spokesman Ahmad 
Fawzi told reporters in New York. 
  "If either party attempts to retrieve those weapons it will 
have to use force and will therefore be in breach of the 
accepted conditions. Force will in turn be used against it," 
Fawzi said. 
  Serbian and Bosnian Moslem forces are due to withdraw their 
heavy weapons from a 20-kilometer (12-mile) radius of Sarajevo, 
or hand them over to UN control, by 0000 GMT Sunday or risk NATO 
airstrikes. 
  Bosnian Serbs said Thursday they would withdraw their heavy 
weaponry in time, following an intervention by Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

