<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reports `Significant' Serb Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702204894 Paris AFP in English 2037 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo, Feb 17 (AFP) -- Bosnian Serb convoys 
carrying equipment and heavy weapons were seen quitting the 
hills around Sarajevo Thursday [12 February] in what military 
observers viewed as a "major, very significant" withdrawal, a 
spokesman said. [passage omitted] 
  "Today the UNMOs (military observers) gave us reports of 
very 
significant withdrawal of Serb forces of the hills around 
Sarajevo," UN Protection Force Lieutenant-Colonel Bill Aikman 
said. 
  "Up until now, the reports from the UNMOs have been of 
individual vehicles and pieces of equipment. Today, they're 
talking about convoys of equipment moving out of the hills," he 
added. 
  "A major, very significant withdrawal is going on," he said. 
  General Michael Rose, commander of the UN Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) in Bosnia, "has received information from senior 
levels of the Bosnian Serb government that they will have their 
equipment out of a 20-kilometer (12-mile) zone within 36 hours, 
that means well before the deadline of midnight Sunday night," 
Aikman added. 
  Journalists in and around the capital however saw no 
immediate sign of the withdrawal. 
  There was no new activity at the Lukavica barracks, main 
headquarters of Serb forces in the Sarajevo suburbs. And 
armoured vehicles deployed along the front line in front of the 
barracks which had disappeared in the previous few days were 
again put into combat position Thursday. [passage omitted] 
  Aikman said UNPROFOR's contingent in Sarajevo was continuing 
to receive reinforcements and its staff now numbered 3,500 men, 
an increase of 500 in less than a week. 
  A British armoured unit consisting of 170 men, equipped with 
14 Warrior tanks, was expected to arrive here from the central 
Bosnian town of Vitez on Friday. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

