<H3> <TI>   Weapons To Be Withdrawn to 7 Locations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802153594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1444 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lukavica, 18 Feb (TANJUG) -- Republic of Srpska 
president Radovan Karadzic stated today following talks with the 
UN secretary general's special envoy for former Yugoslavia, 
Yasushi Akashi, that the Srpska army planned to withdraw its 
heavy artillery from around Sarajevo until midnight tomorrow [19 
February]. 
  "We have set a certain deadline and it is 2400 [2300 GMT] 
tomorrow, regardless of other deadlines," Karadzic said. 
  He added that the Srpska army had already withdrawn a number 
of convoys of heavy weapons and that they were still 
withdrawing. Those that cannot be withdrawn due to the snow will 
be under full UN control, Karadzic said. 
  "From noon tomorrow [1100 GMT 19 February], UN members will 
control seven locations where heavy weaponry will be assembled," 
Akashi told journalists. 
  This refers to five locations where the Serbs ought to 
assemble their artillery and two locations where the Muslims are 
to assemble theirs. 

</TEXT>

