<H3> <TI>   Karadzic, UN Envoy Akashi Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802131894 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1214 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802131894 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lukavica, 18 Feb (TANJUG) -- Radovan Karadzic, 
president of the Srpska republic, and Yasushi Akashi, the UN 
secretary general's special envoy for former Yugoslavia, met in 
Lukavica today to discuss issues concerning the implementation 
the Russian initiative, the control and the withdrawal of Serb 
artillery, and the observance of the Sarajevo cease-fire. 
  Speaking at a news conference, Colonel Richard Pernod, head 
of the UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] Sarajevo sector press 
center, could not confirm that the Serb artillery had already 
begun withdrawing. 
  Asked what was happening on the territory of Sarajevo, 
Pernod 
explained that weaponry was being assembled, and expressed the 
hope that the Serb and the Muslim sides would begin withdrawing 
within the envisaged period. 
  He added that "convoys were being formed on the Serb side" 
in 
five locations: Lukavica, Mokro, Vela, Blagovat, and Saracevac. 
As regards the Muslim army, these locations are Malo Polje and 
Marshal Tito barracks. 
  Asked whether the Serb convoys would move in the next 24 
hours, Pernod replied: "Naturally, the withdrawal should begin 
today, but so far I have no information." TANJUG has learned 
from Serb sources that more than 100 Serb artillery pieces on 
the territory of Sarajevo have already been put under control 
[as received], and that the handover of heavy artillery will be 
completed within the deadline agreed on with UN representatives. 

</TEXT>

