<H3> <TI>   Lukic: Civilians Not Threatened by Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802134994 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1229 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Obrenovac, 18 Feb (TANJUG) -- We are not abandoning 
Serb citizens in Sarajevo, nor are their lives in danger due to 
the withdrawal of a part of the heavy weaponry from a zone of 20 
kilometers surrounding Sarajevo, the prime minister of the 
Srpska republic, Vladimir Lukic, has told Radio Obrenovac [local 
radio in Serbia]. 
  Another part of the weaponry will be placed under UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] control; therefore, the reason for NATO 
air strikes no longer exists, prime minister Lukic said. 
  Replying to the question of when the Russian UNPROFOR 
soldiers could be expected to arrive in Sarajevo, Lukic did not 
specify the time but said that their deployment along frontlines 
would be an opportunity for the world finally to understand that 
it is not only one side -- the Muslims -- that care about peace. 

</TEXT>

