<H3> <TI>   Muslims Boycott Tripartite Commission Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702131194 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1157 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1702131194 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zvornik, 17 Feb (TANJUG) -- Major General Manojlo 
Milovanovic, chief of general staff of the army of the Serb 
Republic [in Bosnia-Herzegovina], told TANJUG today that the 
Sarajevo cease-fire agreement is mainly being observed, but that 
the Muslim side has called into question an important part of 
the agreement, which was reached at Sarajevo Airport on 9 
February. 
  This morning, without any explanation, the Muslim side 
refused to send its representatives to participate in the 
continuation of the work of a tripartite commission, which has 
already shown results, Milovanovic said. The task of the 
commission, made up of representatives of the Serb and the 
Muslim sides and UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] officers, is to 
draw up a solution for the control of the cease-fire. 
  The commission should have reached practical solutions on 
the 
basis of a direct insight into the situation in the field, which 
for the most part has been done, between 10 February and today, 
Gen. Milovanovic explained. 
  Due to the discontinuation of the work of the joint 
commission, it is necessary to hold a meeting as early as today 
between Serb and Muslim corps commanders and UNPROFOR troops in 
Sarajevo, Milovanovic said. 
  He added that by hampering the work of the tripartite 
commission the Muslim side has shown how much importance it 
attaches to the control and observance of the cease-fire in the 
Sarajevo area. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

