<H3> <TI>   Ambassador to Tehran Interviewed on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC1702083994 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0430 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1702083994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on an interview with Ambassador Omar Bahman of </F>
Bosnia-Herzegovina by correspondent Qoroqi in Tehran on 17 
February -- recorded] 
  [Text] In an interview with the Central News Unit, Omar 
Bahman, ambassador from the Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, 
described the situation in Bosnia as extremely disturbing and 
called on international forums and especially on Islamic 
countries to adopt a serious decision. 
  [Begin recording of Omar Bahman in unidentified language 
with 
superimposed correspondent's report in Persian] Referring to 
recent NATO decisions for air operations in Bosnia, he said: 
This decision should have been made a long time ago. The 
situation in Bosnia has now reached such a stage that such 
temporary steps--even though positive--cannot solve the Bosnian 
people's problem. 
  Criticizing UN actions in Sarajevo and referring to the 
general disarmament in the city, Omar Bahman said: If this 
decision is carried out justly, it can be useful. But past 
experience shows that this step by the United Nations also 
serves the objectives of the Serbs and that in the long run only 
the Muslims will be disarmed since the Serbs can re-arm 
themselves with the support that they have. 
  The Bosnian ambassador in Tehran also described the West's 
political pressure to accept the peace plan as futile, and said: 
The Bosnian people are no longer fooled by the West's false 
slogans. 
  Continuing, Omar Bahman strongly criticized France and 
Russia 
and accused them of conveying the secret decisions adopted by 
NATO and the Security Council to the Serbs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

