<H3> <TI>   Humanitarian Airdrops Continuing </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802140194 Paris AFP in English 1354 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Frankfurt, Germany, Feb 18 (AFP) -- Airdrops of 
emergency aid to the besieged Moslem enclaves in eastern Bosnia 
are continuing despite the threat of air strikes against Serb 
artillery around Sarajevo, a spokesman for the operation 
"Provide Promise" said Friday. 
  "Our operations haven't changed. We are continuing until the 
UN makes a decision otherwise," a spokesman at the Rhein-Main 
airbase said. 
  During Thursday night 11 planes dropped 78 tonnes of food, 
2.5 tonnes of medical supplies and just under six tonnes of 
clothing and blankets, Airman Stuart Camp said. 
  Since the start of the operation on Feruary 27, 1993, US, 
French and German transporter planes have dropped some 16,700 
tonnes of food, medical aid and winter supplies, he said. 

</TEXT>

