<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   RSK Leader Cited on UNPROFOR Departure </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702203794 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1808 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1702203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Pool" item] </F>
  [Text] Vukovar, Feb 17 (TANJUG) -- The deputy defense 
minister of the Republic of Serb Krajina (R.S.K.) Milan 
Milanovic Thursday warned UNPROFOR [UN Protection Forces] of 
possible undesirable consequences if parts of Russian and 
Belgian battalions leave the eastern UNPA [UN protected areas] 
sector for Sarajevo. 
  If that happens, Milanovic warned Commander Jean Cot, the 
situation in eastern Slavonia, Baranja and western Srem will be 
very difficult as no one will be left to ensure the 
disengagement of the R.S.K. (Serb state in Croatia) forces and 
the Croatian Army, which was precisely the reason why the two 
battalions had come to the eastern sector. 
  It could also happen that the population will prevent the 
departure of U.N. troops, Milanovic said, adding he also 
believed it would be better if they remained where they are now. 
  The UNPROFOR commander for Bosnia-Herzegovina British 
General 
Sir Michael Rose has asked for additional 3,000 troops to 
control the demilitarization of the 20 km exclusion zone around 
Sarajevo, capital of the war-torn former Yugoslav Republic of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, neighboring on the eastern UNPA sector. 
  According to the eastern sector information service, French 
General Cot, whose headquarters are based in Croatia's capital 
Zagreb, is expected to arrive in Erdut on March 1 for a farewell 
visit to the area before handing over his duties to a successor. 

</TEXT>

