<F P=101> Bulgaria </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tatarchev, Grigorov Denounce Judicial Amendments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602211794 Sofia BTA in English 1838 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602211794 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Prosecutor-General Tatarchev: Judiciary Organization Bill </F>
Aims at Temporary Restoration of Communism" -- BTA headline] 
  [Text] Sofia, February 16 (BTA) -- Prosecutor-General Ivan 
Tatarchev said the text of the Judiciary Organization Bill which 
passed yesterday achieves a temporary restoration of communism. 
  The new provision requires that the chairmen of the Supreme 
Court of Cassation and the Supreme Administrative Court, the 
prosecutor-general and the director of the National 
Investigative Service have 14-year service in the legal 
profession, of which at least five years as judges, prosecutors 
or investigators. According to jurists, the incumbent 
prosecutor-general Ivan Tatarchev and Supreme Court Chairman 
Ivan Grigorov, both of them lawyers, are ineligible for a second 
term. Thus only people linked to the former Communist Party 
will qualify for the top positions in the judiciary. 
  Asked by BTA what will become of the lawsuits against the 
culprits for Bulgaria's economic catastrophe if he is dismissed, 
Tatarchev said in his view they would sink into oblivion. 
  Supreme Court Chairman Ivan Grigorov said the full 
recommunization of all areas yesterday hit the judiciary. "God 
save the non-Communists in Bulgaria," Grigorov added. 
  The new provision was sponsored by Asen Michkovski MP of the 
New Union for Democracy. Zlatka Ruseva, deputy floor leader of 
the Union of Democratic Forces (SDS), described it as 
discriminatory and aimed at recommunization. She said the SDS 
would approach the Constitutional Court with a request to repeal 
the law. 
  The bill is unlikely to be enacted in the near future, 
according to MP's, because many points remain to be debated. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

