<H3> <TI>   Jan Unemployment Reaches 16.53 Percent </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1602211694 Sofia BTA in English 1843 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1602211694 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia BTA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sofia, February 16 (BTA) -- Unemployment in 
Bulgaria hit 16.53 percent of the workforce in late January 
1994, rising 0.15 points from December 1993, the National 
Employment Service with the Ministry of Labour and Social 
Affairs today told BTA. 
  The unemployed numbered 632,000. The jobless rate was 
highest in Montana (northwestern Bulgaria) (23.9 percent) and 
lowest in Sofia (8.3 percent). Only one-third have a right to a 
compensation or social benefits. Data shows the number of 
jobless persons under 30 kept falling as it did in late 1993, 
which is seen as a positive trend. 
  Job vacancies in late January numbered 8,200, with 77 
jobless 
vying for a single vacancy. Most positions were to be found in 
Sofia. 
  In January alone, the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs 
paid out 240.6 million leva in benefits and spent nearly 3 
million leva on retraining. 

</TEXT>

