<H3> <TI>   Committee: Air Strike Resolution `Significant' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802083494 Prague CTK in English 2307 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802083494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Feb 17 (CTK) -- The parliamentary Foreign 
Committee considers the UN Security Council and NATO Council 
resolution on the possibility of air strikes in defence of the 
civilian population of Sarajevo a significant step towards 
creating conditions for a political resolution to the conflict 
through talks in Geneva, CTK learnt today. 
  The Foreign Committee believes air strikes do not represent 
a 
solution in themselves if the warring sides do not reach 
agreement. Consequently it recommends the opposing sides to 
accept the NATO resolution as an emphatic call for the search 
for a durable solution to the crisis, the Foreign Committee 
resolution reads. 
  The NATO ultimatum requires the Bosnian Serbs to withdraw 
their artillery from surrounding Sarajevo and turn them over to 
UN control by February 21. If they do not comply they face 
bombing by American, French and British aircraft. 

</TEXT>

