<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Fails To Accept World Bank Loans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802083894 Prague CTK in English 2228 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802083894 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 16 (CTK) -- The frozen discussions 
between the World Bank and the Czech Government concerning loans 
of $225 million for aid to North Bohemia are not connected to 
the fact that state guarantees, being able to amount to not more 
than eight percent of the state budget, have already been 
exhausted for this year, said Premier Vaclav Klaus after today's 
cabinet meeting. 
  He said that the government had accepted by no means all of 
the World Bank offerings, and added that regardless of whether 
the Czech Republic should or should not accept loans offered by 
the World Bank, or whether or not they complied with the aims of 
the country, scores of meetings would have to be conducted. 
  Klaus stated that the government was aware that the 
possibility to cover loans with state guarantees had been at its 
limit for a few years, but that this limit had never been 
breached. 
  The government carefully followed the provision of 
guarantees, he said. Nevertheless, during consideration of the 
provision of a guarantee for construction of the 
Decin-Praha-Breclav railway link, Finance Minister Ivan Kocarnik 
had been requested to put forward data on the provision of state 
guarantees for previous years. 

</TEXT>

