<F P=101> Hungary </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Chairman Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802134894 Budapest MTI in English 1257 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802134894 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 18 Feb (MTI) -- Hungarian Prime Minister 
Peter Boross is sending a letter to NATO Secretary-General 
Manfred Woerner, in which he will ask that the AWACS aircraft 
not be in Hungarian airspace during air strikes on Bosnia, 
reported the chairman of Parliament's Foreign Affairs Committee, 
Laszlo Kovacs, after a closed joint session of the Foreign and 
Defence Committees. MPs supported the government and agreed 
that Hungary should not be affected in any military action, even 
indirectly. 
  "The demonstrative absence mainly serves to reassure 
Belgrade, indicating that Hungary wants to avoid even the 
semblance of participating in military action," Kovacs said. 
  He recalled that no parliamentary approval is necessary to 
let AWACS patrol in Hungarian airspace, or to ban them: The 
government decides on this alone. But parliamentary 
authorisation would be needed for NATO to ask that these 
aircraft take part in military actions. Kovacs said no such 
request has arrived from NATO. 
  He admitted there was a dilemma in Hungary holding back from 
the conflict yet at the same time protecting relations with NATO. 

</TEXT>

