<H3> <TI>   Deak Nominated for Position of Army Commander </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702114494 Budapest MTI in English 1900 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702114494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest MTI </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Budapest, 16 Feb (MTI) -- The Defence Committee of 
Hungarian Parliament on Wednesday [16 February] held a hearing 
for Lieutenant General Janos Deak, whom the minister of defence 
proposed for the post of commander of the Hungarian Army. The 
committee unanimously supported the nomination. 
  The general, who is also chief-of-staff of the Army, is to 
replace Colonel-General Kalman Lorincz, who is retiring. The 
appointment will be signed by the president of the Republic of 
Hungary, who is the commander-in-chief of the Army. 
  During the 90-minute hearing, Deak stated that the mood 
among 
officers is not too good. He said that improving this is not 
merely a financial issue, but that the social prestige of 
military careers must also be increased. 
  There is presently a shortage of officers out among the 
troops, according to Deak. On the other hand, there are 13,000 
officers in the army. In his view, this number is overly high 
and should be readjusted to around 8,000. Deak also said 
replacements should be ensured not merely from the military 
colleges, but also from the university of arts and sciences, and 
the technical university. 

</TEXT>

