<H3> <TI>   Holds Talks With Pawlak </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602231294 Warsaw PAP in English 2247 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602231294 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 16 -- Prime Minister Waldemar Pawlak 
received Moldovan Foreign Minister Ion Botnaru to discuss 
conditions for a more animated economic cooperation between 
their countries, and joint undertakings on the third markets. 
  Wednesday was the last day of the Moldovan minister's visit 
to Poland. Botnaru met with leaders of the Polish Economic 
Chamber (KIG), including its President Marek Kloczko, to discuss 
the development of economic cooperation in conditions of 
economic transformations underway in both countries. 
  Botnaru stressed that Moldova is interested in the 
development of cooperation in the field of food processing and 
chemical industry. 13 joint economic undertakings are being 
implemented at present and two new ones are to be launched in 
the nearest future. 
  Ion Botnaru paid a visit to the Democratic Left Alliance 
(SLD) headquarters in Warsaw. 
  On Tuesday, the Moldovan guest and foreign minister Andrzej 
Olechowski initialled a treaty on friendship and cooperation 
between Poland and Moldova and signed a protocol on mutual 
consultations between their ministries. 
  Olechowski announced that the treaty would be signed during 
the Polish visit of Moldovan President Mircea Snegur scheduled 
for the first half of 1994. He added that the Polish Embassy in 
Chisinau will be opened this year. 
  Also on Tuesday Botnaru was received by deputy Sejm and 
Senate speakers, Jozef Zych and Ryszard Czarny respectively, and 
met with Chairman of the Sejm Foreign Affairs Committee 
Bronislaw Geremek. 

</TEXT>

