<F P=101> Poland </F>
<H3> <TI>   Olechowski Notes Priorities in Eastern Policy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1702214094 Warsaw PAP in English 2059 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1702214094 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 17 -- Foreign Minister Andrzej 
Olechowski told the Senate foreign affairs committee on Thursday 
that Poland would open a new chapter in her eastern policy. He 
said that the policy towards countries situated east of Poland 
should focus on developing good relations with those which were 
important from the viewpoint of Polish political and economic 
interests and Polish security. 
  Olechowski stated that the countries of special interest to 
Poland were Russia, Ukraine, Belarus, the Baltic states, Moldova 
and Kazakhstan. 
  "We want the climate of our relations with Russia to warm 
up," the minister told senators. He added that the desired 
openness and friendliness of relations with Russia would depend 
on whether Russia respected the strategic option of the Polish 
foreign policy, ie. Poland's striving to join the European 
Union, NATO and the Western European Union. Olechowski added 
that the neo-imperial option in Russian foreign policy had to be 
regarded as a real threat. 
  He said the independence of Ukraine was of strategic 
importance for Poland. "We will act in favour of Ukraine's 
acquiring a position in international relations reflecting her 
potential," said the minister. 
  Olechowski also voiced support for the process of uniting 
the 
west and the east and stressed that by taking part in the 
Partnership for Peace initiative Poland not only strove for NATO 
membership, but also wanted to cooperate with Russia, Ukraine, 
Belarus and Lithuania. 
  The minister announced Polish support for the development of 
market relations and democracy in the countries east of Poland. 
He said he would appoint a commissioner for eastern policy and 
propose that the government establish a council for eastern 
policy. 

</TEXT>

