<H3> <TI>   Ministry Reduces Limitations on State Secrets </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1602211994 Warsaw PAP in English 2013 GMT 16 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1602211994 </F>
<F P=104>  Warsaw PAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb. 16 -- The interior ministry, after 
consultations with the Defence Ministry, the Central Office of 
Planning and the Justice Ministry, reduced the number of news 
that under a government-proposed draft law would be treated as 
state secrets, department director in the Interior Ministry 
Ryszard Taradejna announced Wednesday. A special Sejm 
subcommittee has been working on the draft since December 1993. 
  The penal chamber of the Supreme Court on Wednesday ruled 
that parliamentary immunity relates not only to the operation of 
a deputy in the Sejm and its committees but also to his/her 
activity outside the chamber if it falls in line with 
parliamentary functions. 
  The ruling may be essential for the final dropping of a 
trial 
of leader of Centre Alliance (PC) Jaroslaw Kaczynski charged 
with violating state secrets in 1992 while revealing an 
instruction of the State Protection Office (UOP). 

</TEXT>

