<H3> <TI>   SDL Chairman on Early Elections, Meciar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802072094 Prague CTK in English 2053 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802072094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, February 17 (CTK) -- Dismissing Premier 
Vladimir Meciar and his government before the amendment to the 
Law on Large Privatization is passed and a decision on early 
elections made is not a good idea, chairman of Slovakia's 
strongest opposition party, the Democratic Left Party (SDL) 
Peter Weiss said today. 
  After the opposition's failure in parliament today to have a 
law on early elections passed, Weiss said that he gave priority 
to negotiations by all parliamentary parties on the date of the 
elections. He also said that the parliament could bind the 
president to calling a referendum on early elections in November. 
  Weiss expressed the suspicion that Meciar's campaign for a 
referendum would be led in such a way so that voters agreed with 
the exit from the Movement for a Democratic Slovakia (HZDS) of 
those deputies who had infringed party discipline, and would say 
no to early elections. Meciar would also try and join in the 
referendum the question of the date of the elections and that of 
whether deputies who had left the party to which they were 
elected should be expelled from parliament, Weiss said. 
  With this scenario, Weiss said, "difficult" politicians 
could 
be removed from parliament and the parliamentary support of the 
present government coalition would be guaranteed until the end 
of the regular electoral term in 1996. However, this idea would 
meet with "great resistance" from the public, Weiss said. 

</TEXT>

