<H3> <TI>   Import Restrictions on Czech Food Lifted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802083594 Prague CTK in English 2008 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 17 (CTK) -- Until March 31 Slovak 
customs authorities will require the same documents and 
certificates at the Czech border as they did before February 11, 
a Slovak Finance Ministry spokesman informed CTK today. Finance 
Minister Julius Toth's decision became effective straight after 
the Wednesday [16 February] meeting of the Customs Union Council 
(RCU). 
  Today the decision was discussed with Slovak customs 
authorities, the spokesman said. 
  The documents specified in the agreement between the Czech 
and Slovak offices for normalization, metrology, and inspection 
will be required at the border after March 31. Toth's decision 
states that the two sides must agree on mutual recognition of 
testing procedures and certificates. 
  Yesterday Slovakia withdrew from the sudden and unilateral 
requirement it made on February 11 according to which no food 
products could be imported into the country without a quality 
certificate issued by Slovak organs. Officials said the measure 
was inspired by concern to limit the import of poor quality food 
products. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

