<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Last of Russian MiG-29 Fighters Delivered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702175094 Prague CTK in English 0814 GMT 17 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1702175094 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava, Feb 17 (CTK) -- The last MiG-29 fighter 
of the six with which Russia is partially paying off the debt of 
the former Soviet Union to Slovakia landed in Slovakia last 
night, a spokeswoman for the Slovak Defense Ministry told CTK. 
  On November 30, 1993, Slovakia and Russia signed an 
agreement 
to partially decreasing the debts of the former Soviet Union and 
the Russian Federation to the Slovak Republic through supplies 
of special equipment. 
  Under the agreement, Slovakia bought in December weapons and 
military equipment worth $180 million, including six MiG-29 
fighters and spare parts for various types of weapons. 
  During his January visit to Moscow, Slovak Defense Ministry 
State Secretary Igor Urban and his Russian partners reached an 
agreement that Slovakia will purchase other military equipment, 
mainly spare parts, worth $80 million. 

</TEXT>

