<F P=100> CZECH REPUBLIC </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Previews Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1902092794 Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network in Czech 0600 
GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1902092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague Radiozurnal Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Czech </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Announcer] Russian Minister of Foreign Affairs 
Andrey Kozyrev arrived in Prague yesterday on a working visit. 
Correspondent David Stahlavsky talked with Kozyrev about his 
planned talks with Czech officials. 
  [Stahlavsky] The Russian foreign minister is convinced that 
the talks will concern the Bosnian issue, among other things, 
because the stability of the Central and East European region is 
in the interests of all. Andrey Kozyrev said that relations 
between the Czech Republic and Russia are based on history and 
enjoy good prospects. An assessment should be made of the ways 
in which European partnership could be developed. This 
assessment should be free of prejudice and mutual suspicions. 
  Kozyrev told Czech Radio that he is against reviving the old 
doctrines on the inequality of relations. The main thing is to 
build a new, big, and united Europe. The Russian minister of 
foreign affairs emphasized that no one has a ready-made 
prescription for doing this. He went on to add: 
  [Begin Kozyrev recording in Russian, fading to superimposed 
Czech translation] Partnership for Peace is one of the variants 
for joining NATO. We do not prevent anyone from doing so 
because this is a matter on which all of the states, including 
the Czech Republic, will have to decide themselves. [end 
recording] 
  [Stahlavsky] But Andrey Kozyrev emphasized that there is no 
need to focus only on NATO and recalled the existence of the 
Visegrad Four, the CSCE, and others. There is no need to work 
against these forms of cooperation. All of the options should 
be used in the interest of political, economic, and cultural 
benefit, Kozyrev said. 

</TEXT>

