<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tudjman Receives Redman, Praises U.S. Position </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102192594 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
1800 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102192594 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In the presidential palace today, Croatian President 
Franjo Tudjman received Ambassador Charles Redman, the U.S. 
President's special envoy at the conference on the former 
Yugoslavia. Redman was accompanied by Ambassador to Croatia 
Peter Galbraith. The meeting was also attended by Jure Radic, 
head of the president's office. Ambassador Redman informed the 
president about positive U.S. attitudes toward the convergence 
of Croatian and Muslim stands regarding the securing of a 
cease-fire and the implementation of a final solution in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  He supported Croatia's approach based on a peaceful solution 
and promised the international community's support in protecting 
the Croatian areas that are under siege at the moment. He 
stressed in particular the United States' readiness and resolve 
to contribute -- in parallel with resolving the 
Bosnia-Herzegovina crisis -- to the establishment of the full 
sovereignty of the Republic of Croatia in all areas within its 
internationally recognized borders, urging the opening of 
communications, and restoration of economic links. 
  President Tudjman thanked the ambassador and the U.S. 
Government for their constructive and active role in resolving 
the crisis in the area of the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

