<F P=100> CROATIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Granic Cited on Talks With Bosnian Muslims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2002195494 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1724 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2002195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade, Feb 20 (TANJUG) -- The talks between the 
Bosnian Muslims and Croatia ended in Frankfurt on Saturday 
without producing any concrete headway in the resolution of 
disputed issues. 
  Although Croatian Foreign Minister Mate Granic and Bosnian 
Muslim Prime Minister Haris Silajdzic said after the talks that 
differences between the two sides had been narrowed, according 
to foreign news agencies, they did concede that the two sides 
were still far from any significant agreement. 
  Granic, who is also deputy Croatian prime minister, said the 
Muslim side was interested in a confederation with Croatia, but 
the two sides were still not in agreement about the future form 
of organization of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Granic said each member 
of the planned confederation would be a member of the United 
Nations. Granic said various ideas about the division of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina into ethnic republics or cantons and a 
ceasefire in central Bosnia had been discussed. 
  Granic and Silajdzic said the talks on future 
Croatian-Muslim 
relations would be resumed in the Croatian capital of Zagreb 
next week at the level of experts, after which they said the two 
of them would most likely meet again. 
  Granic and Silajdzic first separately met with special 
United 
States envoy for Bosnia-Herzegovina, Ambassador Charles Redman. 
Ambassador Redman said he was trying to have the two sides more 
decisively approach the resolution of issues of their future 
coexistence. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

