<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Serb General: Withdrawal Obligations Fulfilled </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102214094 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 2006 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102214094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sarajevo, 21 Feb (TANJUG) -- General Stanislav 
Galic, the commander of the Sarajevo-Romanija Corps, said today 
that his units had fullfilled all the obligations regarding the 
movement of its artillery and its placement under UN control, in 
compliance with the decisions of the Srpska republic army's 
supreme command. 
  "Some very insignificant deviations from the general trend 
of 
the withdrawal were caused by weather conditions, but we are 
ready to agree on that, too, and to finalize that part of the 
job at any moment," General Galisc said. 
  Asked about the current situation in the zone of 
responsibility of the Sarajevo-Romanija Corps, Galic stressed 
the soldiers of his corps were in a state of increased combat 
readiness, primarily because they expected that the Muslim 
forces could take advantage of the current circumstances. 
  "Whoever attacks us is our enemy, and we shall defend 
ourselves to the very end," Galic added. 
  Commenting on the arrival in Sarajevo of the Russian 
UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] battalion Galic said this was a case of 
the Russians coming back to their old, primordial friends and 
that the friendship ought to continue to be fostered. 
  "We welcomed them as brothers, as people, and as soldiers. 
We shall do our utmost to facilitate them in performing their 
task of peacekeeping in the area." 
  "The Russian battalion will be deployed between the warring 
parties; that is, in front of our defense lines. UNPROFOR does 
not have a sufficient number of soldiers to cover the whole 
front line, but the Russians will take certain positions from 
which they will be able to efficiently supervise the 
cease-fire," Galic said, adding that he had visited the Russian 
battalion with General Soubirou, UNPROFOR commander for Sarajevo. 
  Asked what was the subject of his talks today with General 
Michael Rose, Galic gave a brief answer: "General Rose was doing 
his routine tour of the area, and he called on the command of 
the Sarajevo-Romanija corps for consultations over coffee, 
something that is a part of his professional duties and 
cooperation." 

</TEXT>

