<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Izetbegovic Reassures Sarajevo of `Victory' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102215894 Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 2100 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102215894 </F>
<F P=104>  Sarajevo Radio Bosnia-Herzegovina Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following the withdrawal of the Serb aggressor's 
artillery from Sarajevo, Alija Izetbegovic, president of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, gave a statement for Sarajevo TV. 
  [Begin Izetbegovic recording] I believe this is a great 
victory for us. Perhaps it is not a completely clear victory, 
it is not faultless, some things have spoiled our joy a bit. 
But it still remains our victory for we are not being killed 
any more. You can let your children skate freely, they can go 
to school, you can go to the market without fear that someone 
will not return home. This is a great achievement after 22 or 
23 months of misery. 
  This is not their victory, as they want to present it. They 
have even convinced themselves, 500 or 600 years ago when they 
lost their state [in 1389, the Serbs were defeated by the Turks 
in the Kosovo battle] that that was their victory, and not a 
defeat. This is their clear defeat. 
  For eight days they had been hesitating to withdraw their 
weapons, they were making up some kinds of reasons, from 
categorical refusing to different pretexts -- snow, adverse 
weather conditions, and so on. In two days only they were 
forced to take to a headlong flight, leaving behind weaponry in 
their retreat. Do not let yourselves be convinced that this is 
a victory for them as they are now trying to convince themselves 
in those hills up there. They left behind -- handed in -- 262 
pieces of heavy weaponry, including 36 tanks and armored 
vehicles. 
  I think that this is our victory and a first step, first in 
a 
series of good things that are going to happen to this city. 
Electricity and water supply will be better, food supplies will 
be better, convoys carrying food and medicines will enter more 
safely, a kind of spring is coming. Therefore, please celebrate 
this victory and do not be afraid any longer. Of course, we are 
not going to allow the city to be divided. We must not be 
afraid of that either. This is a political solution. They are 
no longer there with their tanks and their guns above our heads. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

