<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bosnian Serb Leader Commends UN Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202125594 Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service in 
Serbo-Croatian 1155 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2202125594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Jagodina, 22 Feb (TANJUG) -- Commenting on the 
situation around Sarajevo, the chairman of the Srpska republic's 
assembly, Momcilo Krajisnik, told Radio Jagodina today that the 
Serb side had asked for impartial mediators from UNPROFOR and 
got them in the UN's Russian units. 
  "UNPROFOR is generally implementing the agreement between 
the 
Serb and Muslim sides very correctly and with good intentions. 
The Serb side not only has no complaints, but it also commends 
the impartial and mediating role of the `international forces,'" 
Krajisnik said. 
  Asked to comment on air strike threats if the Serbs did not 
allow Tuzla airport to open, Krajisnik said: 
  "We do not have anything against the opening of Tuzla 
airport 
if we get guarantees that it will not be used to arm Muslim 
forces, thus prolonging the war. However, those who want to 
open the airport straight away do not have good intentions." 
We, Krajisnik added, also have no complaints about the 
demilitarization of the warring sides in Zepa, Srebrenica, and 
other enclaves because our goal is peace and a demarcation 
between the Serbs, Muslims, and Croats. However, not a single 
percent of Serb territory can be threatened by this act. We 
have opted for a peaceful resolution accompanied by a 
demarcation between the three states in the territory of former 
Bosnia-Herzegovina and any attempt to join the three nations is 
in reality a prolongation of military operations, Krajisnik said. 

</TEXT>

