<H3> <TI>   Vice President Calls UN Ultimatum `Mistake' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102214794 Paris France-2 Television Network in French 
1900 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102214794 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris France-2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sarajevo was blessed with another calm day. 
[passage omitted] Stephane Manier and Marcel Martin report: 
  [Begin recording] [Manier] [passage omitted] Whereas the man 
on the streets keeps turning his bitterness over without really 
realizing that he can now think about it at his leisure, 
politicians look at the situation with more distance: 
  [Ejup Ganic, Bosnian vice president, in English with French 
voiceover] I, for one, did not think that at 0100 last night, 
something would necessarily happen. In the case of an 
ultimatum, you never know when reactions start effectively. 
However, I am worried when I see that there is still quite a 
lot of uncontrolled artillery. It is up to NATO to defend its 
own credibility. We complied and cooperated. The Serbs did 
not. I think that we are now pressing for the Serbs to 
cooperate, but I do believe that the UN made a mistake when it 
negotiated the ultimatum with the Serbs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

