<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cantonization Said Accepted in Muslim-Croat Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1902205794 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2000 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1902205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At this evening's continuation of the Frankfurt 
round of Croatian-Muslim talks, the mutual standpoints are 
drawing closer together. Both delegations, it has been learned, 
have accepted the model of the cantonal organization of the 
future Bosnia-Herzegovina, but some of their standpoints are, 
nevertheless, different. The Muslim side sees the cantons as 
the basis for the development of a future state while the 
Croatian side sees them as only a framework guaranteeing the 
appropriate participation of both nations in the government. In 
this connection, stress is laid on the U.S. initiative on the 
territorial division of Bosnia-Herzegovina into seven cantons. 
  Of the concrete agreements, stress is placed on the 
forthcoming meeting between military commanders General Ante 
Roso and Rasim Delic, which should provide a definite cessation 
of hostilities between the Croatian Defense Council and the 
Muslim army, something that will make further negotiations 
easier. Both delegations agreed with the U.S. approach to the 
talks -- that first there should be an agreement between Croats 
and Muslims on Bosnia-Herzegovina before an agreed proposal is 
put to the third side, the Bosnian Serbs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

