<F P=100> SLOVAKIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meciar Accuses SDL of `Political Blackmail' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802154294 Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802154294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bratislava Rozhlasova Stanica Slovensko Network 
in Slovak 1400 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>Slovak </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar gave an extraordinary 
news conference in Bratislava today at which he accused the 
opposition of attempting to blackmail him to accept the October 
election date. 
  He announced that before noon he had been visited by 
Parliament Chairman Ivan Gasparovic, who had shown him a draft 
resolution by Party of the Democratic Left [SDL] deputies to be 
adopted by the National Council should the prime minister not 
agree to hold early elections in October this year. 
  The resolution proposes to cancel some previous Cabinet 
decisions in the sphere of privatization of enterprises and to 
have the course of action taken by the prime minister and Julius 
Toth, the deputy prime minister and finance minister, 
investigated by the General Prosecutor's Office. The resolution 
calls on the two Cabinet officials to resign. 
  In this context, Vladimir Meciar said that he is asking the 
General Prosecutor's Office to investigate the possibility of 
this being attempted political blackmail. He added that this 
illustrates the deep moral crisis of the politics of the SDL and 
others who participated in this action. 
  Meciar went on to confirm that the Movement for a Democratic 
Slovakia held talks yesterday evening about a broad coalition 
with the representatives of the Slovak National Party, the SDL, 
and the Christian Democratic Movement. However, he rejected 
speculation that he had offered specific ministerial posts to 
SDL Deputy Chairman Peter Kanis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

