<H3> <TI>   Hungarian Civic Party Urges Three-Party Coalition </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102221494 Budapest Kossuth Radio Network in Hungarian 
1700 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2102221494 </F>
<F P=104>  Budapest Kossuth Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hungarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Today the Hungarian Civic Party of Slovakia 
issued a call urging the coalition of three Hungarian parties. 
Our Bratislava correspondent Ildiko Nagy outlines the document. 
  [Nagy] With respect to the activity of the governing party's 
petition committee, which was formed at the weekend, aimed at 
collecting 350,000 signatures to demand a referendum, today the 
Hungarian Civic Party published an appeal. It calls on 
Slovakia's citizens, especially the Hungarian electors, not to 
join the call for a referendum, which [Prime Minister] Meciar 
has been urging. 
  It also calls on the leaders of the Coexistence and the 
Hungarian Christian Democratic Movement to start talks without 
delay in preparation for a Hungarian three-party coalition, with 
regard to the situation that has evolved and the possibility of 
early elections. 
  The need for this coalition is also proved by what 
[Coexistence leader] Miklos Duray said at today's news briefing 
of the Coexistence, namely that prior to last week's parliament 
session the Slovak opposition had not held talks with the 
Hungarian parliamentary coalition on cooperation. [passage 
omitted] 

</TEXT>

