<F P=100> YUGOSLAVIA </F>
<F P=101> Federal </F>
<H3> <TI>   Prime Minister Views Talks With Butrus-Ghali </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1902165594 Belgrade Radio Beograd Network in 
Serbo-Croatian 1400 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1902165594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade Radio Beograd Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone statement by Prime Minister Radoje Kontic in New </F>
York; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] Yesterday started with a meeting with Cardinal 
O'Connor on sanctions and the humanitarian needs of Yugoslavia. 
I would say that the cardinal had carried out a very impressive 
analysis of the global character of the sanctions and their 
counterproductiveness. We agreed that the sanctions were in fact 
the inability of the international community to find a political 
solution for certain conflicts, and that sanctions were hitting 
the weakest and the most innocent and were, therefore, untenable. 
  The main event of yesterday was the meeting with UN 
Secretary 
General Butrus Butrus-Ghali. These talks concerned the Yugoslav 
crisis and its solution, particularly in view of the latest NATO 
ultimatum concerning the air strikes against the positions of 
the Bosnian Serbs. We agreed that the only just and justifiable 
solution is a political one, a political agreement that could be 
reached among the three warring sides without much interference 
from outside, an agreement that would take into account their 
legitimate interests. We also agreed that the agreement on the 
deployment of a UN peacekeeping battalion between the warring 
sides -- after the withdrawal of the Serb artillery -- is a 
sufficient guarantee for a peaceful outcome to the crisis around 
Sarajevo -- that is, the demilitarization of Sarajevo -- and 
that this in effect removed all reasons for a possible air raid 
by NATO against the Serb positions. 
  I would say that the secretary general had a positive 
attitude toward out request for the lifting of the sanctions, 
but he stressed that this depends not only on him and his views 
but primarily on the Security Council members -- that is, some 
of its members, who are still not ready to do so. We said he 
preferred a gradual lifting of the sanctions, just as they were 
imposed. At our request for the reintegration of Yugoslavia 
into the United Nations, I think he reacted positively, but he 
also stressed that this also depended on the General Assembly. 
He suggested that we start preparing the ground for our return 
to the United Nations. 
  I personally think that he was slightly surprised by the 
hard 
attitude, which I presented to him, that the Commission for 
Sanctions was taking when it came to giving permission connected 
to humanitarian aid, the humanitarian needs of the FRY [Federal 
Republic of Yugoslavia]. Of course, this relates primarily to 
energy suppliers and raw materials for medicine. He promised 
that he would intervene with the Commission for Sanctions so as 
to make it have a more benevolent attitude, and he personally 
asked to be informed about my talks with the chairman of the 
Commission for Sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

