<F P=100> The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Neighbors Agree To Help Break Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802194094 Paris AFP in English 1934 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Sofia, Dec 18 (AFP) -- Countries bordering 
Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] 
agreed on Friday [18 February] to set up a supply corridor to 
the country, to help break a controversial trade embargo imposed 
by Greece. 
  Transport officials from Turkey, Bulgaria, Albania and Italy 
and Macedonia told journalists they had agreed on a road and 
rail link to the former Yugoslav republic, which would be 
coordinated in the Bulgarian capital. 
  The creation of such a corridor was an "urgent necessity" 
after Greece's decision Wednesday to bar Macedonia access to the 
Greek port of Salonika, halting its oil imports, the country's 
deputy Transport Minister Yorgo Sundovski said at a press 
conference. [passage omitted] 
  Greece's EC partners sharply criticised the trade embargo on 
Friday. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

