<F P=100> BOSNIA-HERZEGOVINA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sarajevo Solution Seen as Model for Other Cities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102194094 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1858 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102194094 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Feb 21 (TANJUG) -- U.N. Secretary General 
special envoy for former Yugoslavia Yasushi Akashi stated on 
Monday that the solution for the partial demilitarization of 
Sarajevo will be a model for other cities in the former Yugoslav 
Republic of Bosnia-Herzegovina, for example Mostar. 
  Fighting has been going on for one year already in Mostar, 
southern Bosnia-Herzegovina, between Bosnian Moslems and Croats 
for domination over the city. 
  If there are no grave breeches of the ceasefire in the 
region 
of Sarajevo, we could say that the possibility that NATO air 
strikes be launched in Bosnia is longer existant, Akashi said in 
an interview to Japanese television. 
  Serbs and Moslems have complied with NATO's demand that by 
midnight February 20 heavy weapons around Sarajevo be withdrawn 
or placed under U.N. control, therefore according to UNPROFOR 
[UN Protection Forces] headquarters, NATO air strikes are not 
necessary. 
  The ceasefire, which was signed last Wednesday by Serbian 
and 
Moslem forces in Sarajevo, is also respected. 
  Akashi said he hoped that new agreements between the warring 
sides will be reached soon. The economic and social life in 
Sarajevo could be renewed and citizens could leave and enter the 
city freely, he said. 
  Akashi explained that NATO's threats of air strike have had 
a 
specific role in achieving the partial demilitarization of 
Sarajevo, but that other factors have also helped. 
  The complete calming of the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina 
cannot be achieved for several months yet, Akashi assessed and 
added that the U.N. will continue to use the carrot and stick 
method, to bring the warring sides to an agreement. 
  Akashi considered that the three warring sides in Bosnia- 
Herzegovina, Moslem, Serbian and Croatian, will form three 
republics, gathered in a federal Bosnia-Herzegovina. Akashi 
said he hoped that the earlier communal life would be possible 
once again. 
  The plan to divide Bosnia-Herzegovina into three ethnic 
republics, supported by the European Union and on the basis of 
which peace negotiations on Bosnia-Herzegovina are being led, is 
accepted by Bosnian Serbs and Croats, and rejected by Moslems. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

