<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Bosnia-Herzegovina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Koljevic Calls Baudys Plan `Very Interesting' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202120694 Prague CTK in English 1131 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2202120694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Belgrade Feb 22 (CTK) -- Nikola Koljevic, spokesman 
of the Bosnian Serbs, today described as very interesting Czech 
Defence Minister Antonin Baudys' proposal for solving the 
conflict in Bosnia. 
  Baudys' proposal consists mainly in setting up a 
seven-member 
Executive Committee of Good Will (ECGW), including countries 
"connected by their religious and cultural values" to the 
warring groups in Bosnia. Russia, Greece, Pakistan, Turkey, 
France and Italy could become members of such a committee, 
Baudys suggested on Saturday [19 February]. 
  "For us it is a new proposal. It should be discussed in 
Skupstina (parliament). Nevertheless it is very interesting 
especially because it is a practical proposal," Koljevic, 
vice-president of the Serbian Republic in Bosnia, told CTK by 
telephone from Pale near Sarajevo. 
  At the same time, he voiced certain doubts over "the 
possibility of implementation of the proposal in practice." 
Difficulties would arise in connection with full disarmament 
which has been already unambiguously rejected by the Moslem side 
at the Geneva talks, he said. 
  "However at least the restriction of weapons could certainly 
be discussed. It would represent great progress since a truce, 
if not peace, could be more easily achieved by this and the 
antagonistic ethnic groups would have greater certainty. This 
would be more realistic," Koljevic said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-31638 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreeu036__a94006" </HT>


