<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Baudys' Peace Plan for B-H Noted </TI></H3>
<H4>   Baudys: Constitution Not `Breached' </H4>
<F P=102> AU2302101294 Prague CTK in English 2110 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2302101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Feb 22 (CTK) -- Czech Defence Minister 
Antonin Baudys claimed tonight he neither breached the 
Constitution nor exceeded his powers when he made public his 
personal initiative to solve the Bosnian conflict. 
  Returning from a three-day official visit to Turkey, Baudys 
said the only thing for which he could be reprimanded was that 
he used two military air attaches, in Brussels and Washington, 
to distribute the initiative. 
  "Dismissal of a minister is within the premier's 
jurisdiction 
and I see no reason to resign," he said, adding that he would 
make no further statements on the initiative today. 
  Baudys will meet with Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec later 
tonight. 
  Baudys told journalists that Turkish Foreign Minister Hikmet 
Cetin spoke shortly with him before his departure, which proves 
that "in Turkey, at least, the Czech Republic's interests have 
not been harmed by my initiative proposal." 

</TEXT>

