<F P=101> Czech Republic </F>
<H3> <TI>   Klaus Rejects Criticism of Interview on Sudeten </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302101494 Prague CTK in English 2223 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2302101494 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague Feb 22 (CTK) -- Czech Premier Vaclav Klaus 
said today that in an interview published in the German daily 
FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG on Monday [21 February], he had 
only explained the Czech stance toward individual and collective 
rights regarding the Sudeten German question, and pointed to a 
collective solution being impossible. 
  Speaking to journalists after a ministerial session, Klaus 
said that the Sudeten German question could be solved only on 
the individual level. He was reacting to Monday's statement by 
Christian Schmidt, foreign political spokesman of the 
parliamentary group of Bavaria's Christian Social Union (CSU), 
in which Schmidt criticised Klaus over the interview. 
  Klaus said that each German had the right to apply for 
permanent residence in any country of the world, including the 
Czech Republic. "Individual access on the part of the Czech 
Republic is nothing new," he stressed. 
  In the interview for FRANKFURTER ALLGEMEINE ZEITUNG, Klaus 
called the Sudeten German problems "individually solvable," but 
rejected any "collective settlement" of the question. He said 
the Sudeten German problem was an "unfortunate complication" in 
Czech-German relations, inherited by the Czech Government from 
the past. "Today we cannot settle all the problems we 
inherited," Klaus said in the paper. 
  In his press statement on Monday, headlined "Not Like This, 
Mr. Klaus" Schmidt welcomed Klaus's "evident effort at reviving 
and pushing forward Czech-German relations, which have been cool 
for a while." But at the same time he stressed that, regarding 
the sensitive question of post-war German expellees, it was not 
possible simply to "offer nice sounding sentences which pop in 
the air upon closer inspection." Schmidt said he considered 
Klaus's proposal to settle individually Sudeten German problems, 
which Germany views as open, a similar "soap bubble." 

</TEXT>

