<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moravcik, Ukraine's Zlenko Discuss Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2102174294 Prague CTK in English 1658 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2102174294 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bratislava Feb 21 (CTK) -- Ukraine attaches great 
importance to the development of relations with Slovakia, 
Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko said after a meeting 
with his Slovak counterpart, Jozef Moravcik, today. 
  Zlenko, on a two-day visit to Slovakia is accompanied by 
Minister of External Economic Relations Oleh Slyepichev, 
Economics Minister Roman Shpek and Health Minister Yuriy 
Spizhenko. 
  Zlenko and Moravcik discussed bilateral relations, Ukraine's 
possible joining the Central European Initiative and ethnic 
minorities' issues. 
  "We can say that we hold close or identical views on all the 
issues discussed," stressed Zlenko who will inaugurate the 
Ukrainian Embassy in Slovakia. "In creating future Europe, we 
have many common interests such as solution to the ethnic 
minorities' issues," Moravcik said. 
  Slovakia favours resolving the minorities' issue on the 
basis 
of individual rights, while it refuses the collective rights for 
the minorities, including the right to self-rule, as advocated 
by Hungary. 
  Zlenko said that there was no problem with Ukrainians 
working 
"illegally" in Slovakia now. He added that the situation should 
be settled in a legislative way in the future. 
  There is no problem with the "autonomy for Subcarpathian 
Ruthenia," which is being "artificially created," Zlenko said. 
  The expansion of the Visegrad Four (the Czech Republic, 
Slovakia, Hungary and Poland) by Ukraine was not discussed, 
Moravcik said. 

</TEXT>

