<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Slovakia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arrangements Made With Czechs on Food Imports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302101694 Prague CTK in English 2129 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2302101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Prague CTK </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brno, South Moravia Feb 22 (CTK) -- Slovakia has 
agreed on mutual recognition of national decisions and 
certificates required for import only for goods where the same 
norms are in effect on both sides of the Czech-Slovak border. 
  Slovakia thus rejected the Czech proposal of mutual 
recognition of decisions and certificates for all commodities 
regardless of differences in state norms. 
  The decision was reached at a meeting of representatives of 
both the Czech Republic [CR] and Slovakia today, led by Michal 
Tosovsky and Lubomir Sutek, chairmen of the National Offices for 
Technical Normalisation, Metrology and State Testing. 
  As regards food products, as from April 1 the Slovak 
Agricultural and Food Inspectorate will issue a single 
certificate valid for Slovakia. The decisions taken by the 
Czech authorities will form the basis of the issuing of the 
certificate. 
  Until March 31 the Slovak customs authorities will require 
the same documents it required before February 11, when the 
Slovak customs authorities announced that food products without 
a Slovak quality certificate would not be allowed to enter the 
country. 

</TEXT>

