<F P=100> BULGARIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhelev Dismisses Danger of `Recommunization' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802194194 Sofia Khorizont Radio Network in Bulgarian 1700 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> AU1802194194 </F>
<F P=104>  Sofia Khorizont Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Bulgarian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Zhelyu Zhelev stated as follows in an 
interview for the Sofia Khorizont Radio Network today: 
  No basic reforms have been accomplished in Bulgaria as yet, 
hence it is superficial to talk about recommunization as long as 
we have not restored private property and the land to their 
original owners, as long as we have not achieved a certain stage 
in privatization, and as long as the restitution has not been 
completed. The term recommunization has a meaning only if 
applied to the return of cadres from the old nomenklatura to the 
organs of state power, he pointed out. 
  The opposition is not behaving properly, according to 
President Zhelev. It could have overcome bitterness and mutual 
insults by restoring the old majority of the people who won the 
last elections and who should once more take over the executive 
power in order to promote the reforms. Elections under the 
current circumstances are likely to involve the risk of 
uncertain results, the president stressed. 
  President Zhelev sees the Union of Democratic Forces as a 
democratic coalition rallying the democratic, antitotalitarian, 
and non-communist forces, namely all those who are really called 
upon to carry out the reforms in Bulgaria. 
  This is what determines the future and fate of our country, 
President Zhelev stated at the end of his interview for the 
Khorizont Radio Network. 

</TEXT>

