<F P=100> THE FORMER YUGOSLAV REPUBLIC OF MACEDONIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Delegation Arrives in Skopje To Mediate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2302124994 Paris AFP in English 1230 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2302124994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Skopje, Feb 23 (AFP) -- A European Union delegation 
headed by Dutch Foreign Minister Hans Van der Broek arrived here 
Wednesday to mediate a dispute sparked after Greece slapped a 
trade blockade on Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav Republic of 
Macedonia -- FYROM]. 
  Van der Broek was to meet with Macedonian President Kiro 
Gligorov before heading to Athens where he was to try to 
persuade Greek officials to lift their eight-day blockade 
against the former Yugoslav republic. 
  Greece's partners in the 12-member European Union have 
threatened to take Athens before the European Court of Justice 
unless the dispute is resolved. 
  Athens announced on February 16 that it was blocking all 
trade to Macedonia through the northeastern Greek port of 
Salonika, which handles most of the country's imports including 
oil. 
  Greece justified the move by citing Macedonia's "continual 
provocations and growing irredentist intransigence" and claims 
that Macedonia has territorial ambitions in the northern Greek 
province of the same name. 
  Greek Foreign Minister Carolos Papoulias said Wednesday that 
Athens wishes to have good relations with Macedonia but the 
latter must accept the "logical" demands made by the Greek 
Government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
